There is no addObject() function, to use a THREE.js object in JanusXR you can use this syntax:

      this.tubeObject = this.createObject('object', {
        object: tubeMesh
      });

Replace the vertex modification code with this:

        for (let i = 0; i < vertices.length / pos.itemSize; i++) {
            if (bypass.indexOf(i) > -1) {
                continue;
            }

            const currX = pos.getX(i);
            const currY = pos.getY(i);
            const currZ = pos.getZ(i);
            const x = currX + (0 - Math.random() * (1 / 3));
            const y = currY + (0 - Math.random() * (1 / 3));
            const z = currZ + (0 - Math.random() * (1 / 3));

            pos.setX(i, x);
            pos.setY(i, y);
            pos.setZ(i, z);

            for (let j = 0; j < vertices.length; j += 3) {
                if (
                    vertices[j] === currX &&
                    vertices[j + 1] === currY &&
                    vertices[j + 2] === currZ
                ) {
                    meshRef.current.geometry.attributes.position.array[
                        j
                    ] = x;
                    meshRef.current.geometry.attributes.position.array[
                        j + 1
                    ] = y;
                    meshRef.current.geometry.attributes.position.array[
                        j + 2
                    ] = z;
                    bypass.push(j / 3);
                }
            }
        }

Ok, let's start working on controls. We'll start by adding a control context to our spacezone-player object's create function, which for now only uses the mouse_delta control:

this.controlstate = this.addControlContext('spacezone-player', {
  'targeting': { defaultbinding: 'mouse_delta' }
});

Also add a simple targeting reticle, for now represented by a red sphere with a scale of .1 positioned 1 meter in front of us

Now in our update function, we can look at this.controlstate.targeting and get the x,y delta values for any mousemovement that occurred since the last frame, which we can use to move out targeting reticle object on the x and y axis.

Alright, it's time to add collisions to our asteroids. I think we're going to have to slightly change how we generate the asteroids so we can use our generated meshes as collision meshes.

In our initAsteroids function, when we call this.createObject for our asteroid, we're currently passing in "object: asteroidMesh". Instead, before our call to createObject, let's call this function:

this.loadNewAsset('object', {
  id: 'asteroid-' + i,
  object: asteroidMesh
});

Then in our createObject call, replace the object parameter with 

id: 'asteroid-' + i,

and also add

collision_id: 'astroid_' + i
